f attentiveness—to others, to ourselves, to the world around us, to what is truly worthy of focus. Why is there such great anxiety over attention? What is at stake in understanding attention and the challenges it faces?This book investigates attention from a range of disciplinary perspectives, including philosophy, history, anthropology, art history, and comparative literature. Each chapter begins with a concrete scene whose protagonists are trying—and often failing—to attend. Authors examine key moments in the history of the study of attention; pose attention as a philosophical problem; explore the links between attention, culture, and technology; and consider the significance of attention for conceptualizations of human subjectivity. Readers encounter nineteenth-century experiments in boredom, ornithologists conveying sound through field notations, wearable attention-enhancing prosthetics, students using online learning platforms, and inquiries into attention as a cognitive state and moral virtue.Amid mounting concern about digital mediation of experience, the rise of “surveillance capitalism,” and the commodification of attention, Scenes of Attention deepens the thinking that is needed to protect the freedom of attention and the forms of life that make it possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAttention. 0aVisual perception. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh1 aAlford, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, D. Graham, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChehirian, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowles, Henry M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDicey Jennings, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDow Schüll, Natasha, e